The potentiodynamic polarisation curves of CS in the presence of P-CDs in 0.5 M H2SO4 solution with different concentrations and different immersion times are shown in Fig. 4c–f. The presence of P-CDs in different concentrations of P-CDs shifted both the anodic and cathodic branches of the Tafel curve downwards. It can be seen that the corrosion potential (
E corr
) is shifted in the positive direction and towards a low corrosion current density (
i corr
), indicating that the addition of CIs can effectively inhibit the anodic reaction. The downward depression of the polarisation curve in anodic dissolution indicates a stronger inhibition of the anode. In the cathodic reduction reaction, the current density decreased in parallel with the increase of concentration. It indicates that P-CDs can be adsorbed on the CS surface and hinder the reaction of the active site, thus inhibiting the corrosion.
